I have probably been doing this too long, because I remember there were som=
e scandals about congresspeople trading stocks, and everyone was like =E2=
=80=9Cwell congressional insider trading seems pretty illegal already, but =
just in case let=E2=80=99s pass a law making it illegal,=E2=80=9D and so Co=
ngress passed the STOCK Act, for =E2=80=9CStop Trading On Congressional Kno=
wledge,=E2=80=9D and now it=E2=80=99s extra illegal for congresspeople to t=
rade stocks on the basis of nonpublic information that they learn in their =
jobs. This happened in 2012. I must say that the=C2=A0STOCK Act has signall=
y failed in its core purpose, which was to make the U.S. public confident t=
hat congresspeople are not insider trading stocks, because there are somewh=
at frequent scandals these days about congresspeople making well-timed stoc=
k trades. These scandals lead to occasional inquiries but really=C2=A0no pr=
osecutions,[1] so I assume that for the most part congresspeople are not=C2=
=A0in fact insider trading based on information they get in their jobs, tho=
ugh sometimes the publicly available facts do look kind of bad.But never mi=
nd that, the point is that:=09People do not trust that congresspeople are n=
ot insider trading, and are mad at Congress about it, but=09There is alread=
y a very clear law saying that congresspeople are not allowed to insider tr=
ade.So just writing a law saying =E2=80=9Ccongresspeople are even more not =
allowed to insider trade stocks=E2=80=9D does not seem helpful.[2] The obvi=
ous next move is to instead write a law saying =E2=80=9Ccongresspeople are =
not allowed=C2=A0to trade stocks at all, just in case they are tempted to i=
nsider trade,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and here you go:A pair of Senate Democrats intr=
oduced a bill on Wednesday that would ban members of Congress and their fam=
ilies from making stock trades while in office.The bill, dubbed the Ban Con=
gressional Stock Trading Act, would require that all sitting members of Con=
gress, their spouses and dependent children divest from certain investments=
 or transfer them into a qualified blind trust within 120 days of the legis=
lation being enacted. Incoming members of Congress and their families would=
 have to do the same within 120 days of taking office.The legislation is sp=
onsored by Sens. Jon Ossoff (D-Ga.) and Mark Kelly (D-Ariz.).Here is the=C2=
=A0summary of the bill, and here is the bill text. Basically owning stocks =
or bonds, or derivatives on stocks or bonds, would not be allowed except in=
 a blind trust. Diversified=C2=A0mutual funds and exchange-traded funds are=
 allowed, as are U.S. Treasuries; =E2=80=9Cdiversified=E2=80=9D here means =
that a fund or ETF=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cdoes not have a stated policy=C2=A0of conc=
entrating its investments in any industry,=C2=A0business, single country ot=
her than the United=C2=A0States, or bonds of a single State.=E2=80=9D[3] So=
 broad-market stock funds would be allowed but sector ETFs would not. (Exer=
cises for the reader: Is the ARK Innovation ETF allowed? What about a lever=
aged VIX ETF?)This strikes me as more or less sensible as a general matter,=
 both because in general I am a=C2=A0tiny bit suspicious of people with dem=
anding non-financial jobs who spend a lot of time trading portfolios of ind=
ividual stocks, sorry,[4] and because in particular congresspeople make imp=
ortant decisions that might be=C2=A0influenced=C2=A0by their stock=C2=A0own=
ership. If=C2=A0you go to Congress and ask it to approve a law that is good=
 for America but bad for the profits of health-insurance companies or defen=
se contractors or oil companies or whatever, you do not want Congress to re=
ject the law because too many senators own concentrated positions in the af=
fected stocks. I don=E2=80=99t know how practical an improvement this is =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the health-insurance companies and defense contractors and s=
o forth have other ways of getting senators on their side, and despite the =
name you might still know what you own in a =E2=80=9Cblind trust=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but symbolically I suppose it is nice not to have too =
many congresspeople who appear to have a financial bias in favor of individ=
ual companies.But that is not a point about trading.=C2=A0The advantage=C2=
=A0of this bill is that it restricts=C2=A0owning=C2=A0single stocks,=C2=A0a=
nd that=C2=A0ownership is what creates conflicts of interest.[5]My quibble =
here is that this bill is clearly being introduced in reaction to public co=
mplaints about well-timed congressional trades, and I do not see at all how=
 it could address those complaints? It seems somewhat unusual for Congress =
to get a lot of material nonpublic information about=C2=A0individual compan=
ies. The well-timed congressional trading we have discussed most around her=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0the trading that led to a Justice Department=C2=A0inquiry =
(that was closed without charges) =E2=80=94=C2=A0was when Senator Richard B=
urr dumped a bunch of stocks=C2=A0after he got an intelligence committee=C2=
=A0briefing about the coronavirus in mid-February 2020, just before the sto=
ck market cracked. He happened to sell a bunch of individual stocks, some o=
f which (hotels, etc.) were particularly hard-hit by the pandemic. But if=
=C2=A0he had held only broad index funds, he probably would have sold those=
, and it probably would have worked out well for him (the S&P 500 lost a th=
ird of its value in the five weeks after he sold), and people definitely wo=
uld have thought he insider traded. If the head of the CIA comes to your co=
mmittee and says =E2=80=9Cit's gonna be a disaster, sell everything,=E2=80=
=9D and you sell your S&P 500 index fund, no one will be like =E2=80=9Coh t=
hat seems fine.=E2=80=9DIn fact, we know exactly how that would go.=C2=A0Al=
ongside various congressional trading mini-scandals there has been a medium=
-sized scandal involving well-timed trades at the Federal Reserve; three im=
portant Fed officials have resigned over their trading. Two of those did in=
dividual=C2=A0stock trades, but the most recent resignation is from Richard=
 Clarida, the vice chair of the Fed, whose sin was rotating out of a divers=
ified bond fund into some diversified stock funds on Feb. 27,=C2=A02020, =
=E2=80=9Cone day before Chair Jerome Powell issued a statement flagging pos=
sible policy action as the pandemic worsened.=E2=80=9D Here is Senator=C2=
=A0Elizabeth Warren=E2=80=99s letter asking the Securities and Exchange Com=
mission to investigate Clarida. And, sure,=C2=A0if you work at the Fed you =
will get a certain amount of useful macro=C2=A0information, which you could=
 use to trade broadly diversified market indexes, and then people will get =
mad at you.[6]Anyway, I=E2=80=99ll see you back here in a year, when this b=
ill has been enacted and some senator is in trouble because she got a secre=
t intelligence briefing=C2=A0about who Russia was going to invade next and =
ran out and sold all of her shares in a diversified European stock index fu=
nd. Why would that be better?I don=E2=80=99t exactly know how to solve this=
. One reader suggested allowing congresspeople to trade whatever they want,=
 but only on a multi-month lag. This would be along the lines of  the SEC=
=E2=80=99s proposed changes to Rule 10b5-1 trading plans for corporate exec=
utives: You write down a binding plan to buy or sell stocks or bonds or mut=
ual funds or whatever, you give it to your broker, your broker waits (say) =
four=C2=A0months and then executes whatever you told her to do. If you had =
inside information when you wrote the plan, it=E2=80=99s no longer useful f=
our months later when you trade. Ideally (unlike in the 10b5-1 proposals) t=
he plans are disclosed when they=E2=80=99re written, so your constituents k=
now about it in advance, and they can=E2=80=99t be canceled. Then, when you=
r broker does the trades and everyone is like =E2=80=9Cthese are suspicious=
ly well-timed trades,=E2=80=9D you can say =E2=80=9Cno, they were automatic=
, you knew about them in advance.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s something I guess.=
