   =20
      Deterrence
   =20
 =20
How do you deter financial misconduct? This is, I think, a complicated ques=
tion. There is the standard criminological deterrence debate, in which you =
could either focus on catching as much misconduct as possible (and punishin=
g it somewhat mildly) or instead catch fewer perpetrators but punish them m=
ore harshly to send a message. Arguably financial criminals are=C2=A0especi=
ally=C2=A0subject to deterrence =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are rational cost-benef=
it calculators, they have a lot to lose from being caught, etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but there is also an argument that a lot of financial crime falls in =
gray areas of intent or legality and you can=E2=80=99t deter someone from d=
oing something she doesn=E2=80=99t know is illegal. Anyway though the answe=
r is =E2=80=9Cwhen you catch people doing financial crime you should tweet =
about it=E2=80=9D:This paper presents the first evidence of the effect of f=
inancial regulators=E2=80=99 social media use on corporate and individual b=
ehavior. Using the staggered launch of U.S. Securities and Exchange Commiss=
ion (SEC) regional offices=E2=80=99 Twitter accounts, I find that financial=
 regulators=E2=80=99 presence on social media reduces opportunistic insider=
 trading, customer complaints against investment advisers, and financial mi=
sreporting. Additional tests suggest that the salience and dissemination of=
 regional offices=E2=80=99 enforcement activities via Twitter play a role. =
The deterrence effect of SEC regional offices=E2=80=99 Twitter use is conce=
ntrated among offices with more followers, =EF=AC=81rms with more retail in=
vestors, and advisers with more retail clients. I also show that investors =
react more strongly to enforcement actions after the enforced =EF=AC=81rm=
=E2=80=99s regional office=C2=A0initiates Twitter use. Taken together, the =
results suggest that financial regulators=E2=80=99 use of social media help=
s deter misconduct.That is the abstract to =E2=80=9CRegulating via Social M=
edia: Deterrence E=EF=AC=80ects of the SEC's Use of Twitter,=E2=80=9D by Ji=
njie Lin at Yale. I think in some ways this is a complement to the stuff ab=
out congressional insider trading. If you get the sense that the law is nev=
er enforced and people can do bad financial stuff with impunity, you might =
become sad and cynical and disillusioned, and you might do some insider tra=
ding yourself. If you get the sense that the law is often enforced and that=
 every day your local SEC office is catching people doing bad stuff, maybe =
you=E2=80=99ll follow the law yourself.Or perhaps you=E2=80=99ll study thos=
e enforcement actions closely and get better at=C2=A0insider trading withou=
t getting caught? I guess that might look the same in the data.
