      Things happen
   =20
 =20
Goldman's  Commodities Trading Desk Dodged the Ax and Is Minting Billions A=
gain.=C2=A0Goldman Sachs Postpones Its  Return to Office Again to Wait Out =
the Covid Surge. Robinhood Tells Employees They Can Work From Home Permanen=
tly. Robinhood CFO Doesn=E2=80=99t Plan to Put =E2=80=98Meaningful Amount=
=E2=80=99 of Cash Into Crypto Assets. Americans Say They Need to Earn $128,=
000 to Feel  Financially OK. =E2=80=9CThe Food and Drug Administration (FDA=
 or we) is revoking the standard of identity for French dressing.=E2=80=9D =
Counterfeit bourbon. Richard Handler was bullied in high school for being s=
hort. Pope makes surprise visit to Rome record store, gets classical CD.If =
you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in =
your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you can subscribe to Mon=
ey Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] =E2=80=9CCh=
ris Collins,=E2=80=9D you say, but I disagree. Collins, a former congressma=
n from New York, was arrested and ultimately sentenced to 26 months in pris=
on for insider trading at a congressional picnic, but he insider traded=C2=
=A0by tipping his son about a drug company whose board he was on =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0*not* about congressional business. It=E2=80=99s regular insider trad=
ing by a corporate insider who happened to be in Congress, but it=E2=80=99s=
 not congressional=C2=A0insider trading in the sense we=E2=80=99re talking =
about.[2] =E2=80=9CWe need better enforcement of the existing law,=E2=80=9D=
 you say, but get outta here with that. Prosecutors and regulators have *to=
ns* of incentive to catch congressional insider traders, and people are con=
stantly calling their attention to alleged instances of congressional insid=
er trading.[3] So owning municipal bonds =E2=80=94 directly, or through a y=
our-state=E2=80=99s-bonds mutual fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0is banned? Seems a bit=
 harsh.[4] In part because it seems like an expensive niche hobby. That see=
ms to be broadly true of Congress too, by the way; it seems like congresspe=
ople are not especially good at trading stocks.=C2=A0[5] Conflicts that cou=
ld in theory be resolved by trading. Like if you came to Congress with a re=
ally good bill that would hurt the profits of health insurers, and a powerf=
ul senator owned a bunch of health-insurance stocks, it might be strictly g=
ood for the world if she could quietly dump those stocks before announcing =
her support for the bill. Insider trading! But much better than the alterna=
tive where she can=E2=80=99t dump the stocks so she kills the bill to prote=
ct her investment.[6] I should also point out that Clarida=E2=80=99s trades=
 (buying diversified stock funds) happened two weeks after Burr=E2=80=99s (=
selling a diverse list of individual stocks), during the very beginning of =
coronavirus panic in the U.S. The market was going down.=C2=A0By March 23, =
the market bottom, the S&P 500 was down 33% from where Burr sold and down 2=
5% from where Clarida *bought*. Clarida=E2=80=99s trades were *not* particu=
larly well-timed. (Though he had also done some better trading in the same =
funds a few days earlier, and failed to disclose that.)[7] In private equit=
y it is even worse than this because you are not running a public portfolio=
 that is marked to market every year, you are estimating performance alloca=
tions and getting lumpy realizations when you sell companies.
