<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Private equity fees</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/26356098.267642/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjIvcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybS1nb3QtcmljaC1t=
YWtpbmctcHJpdmF0ZS1lcXVpdHktZmlybXMtcmljaD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTEzMjJfTU9ORVlTVFV=
GRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAxMT=
MmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB38a0f061" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> talked last year</a> about a simple bit of private equity math. If you r=
un a private equity firm, you manage a bunch of people=E2=80=99s money and =
you collect a management fee of, traditionally,=C2=A02% per year. If you ma=
nage $10 billion, you make $200 million a year. It is nice to have an incom=
e of $200 million a year. But it gets better. If you have a fairly reliable=
 income of $200 million a year, you can package it and sell it. If you find=
 an investor who wants a 10% return on their money, you can sell them a $20=
0 million stream of fees for $2 billion right now. Or you can sell them 20%=
 of that stream for $400 million right now, and keep the other 80% =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0now valued at $1.6 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0for yourself.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is good for you, for a few reasons. One is that =
you can get a lot of money right now, to buy yachts or whatever. Another is=
 that now you are a billionaire: If you make $200 million a year, pay 50% i=
n taxes, and save 80% of what=E2=80=99s left, it will take you about 12 yea=
rs or so to become a billionaire (in the sense of having $1 billion of cash=
); if you=C2=A0<em>own a business=C2=A0</em>with that profile and it=E2=80=
=99s valued at $2 billion, then you=E2=80=99re a billionaire right now (in =
the sense of owning a $2 billion business). If you have an income, you accr=
ue wealth gradually; if you=C2=A0<em>own an income stream</em>, you have we=
alth now. This is an entirely metaphysical point =E2=80=94=C2=A0the economi=
cs are the same either way =E2=80=94=C2=A0but I suppose it matters. A third=
 advantage is that if you own a business and sell a portion of that busines=
s then you probably have capital-gains income, while if you just collect fe=
es you have ordinary income, and capital gains are taxed at lower rates tha=
n ordinary income, so you keep more of the money you generate.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so it is quite sensible for the owner-manager=
s of private equity firms to sell their firms, or at least to sell stakes i=
n them. They can do this privately =E2=80=94=C2=A0to, like, meta-private-eq=
uity firms that buy stakes in private equity firms=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0or t=
hey can sell stakes=C2=A0to the public in=C2=A0an initial public offering.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this description oversimplifies private=
 equity in one important respect. If you run a private equity firm, you col=
lect a management fee of about 2% a year, but you also collect a=C2=A0perfo=
rmance fee, traditionally about 20% of the returns you make for your client=
s. If you manage $10 billion and return 15%=C2=A0a year, you make about $20=
0 million a year in management fees and $300 million ($10 billion times 15%=
 returns times 20% performance fee) a year=C2=A0in performance fees.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is nice for you. But it is harder to=C2=A0<e=
m>sell</em>. Past performance does not guarantee future results, and if you=
 return 15% this year you might return 0% next year.[7] An investor looking=
 for a steady stream of income might look at your stream of management fees=
 and say =E2=80=9Cthis is a good stream of fees, you seem to have some loya=
l clients, I am willing to bet that you=E2=80=99ll keep collecting fees muc=
h like this for a good long time=E2=80=9D and buy that stream of fees for a=
 high price. That investor might look at your stream of performance fees an=
d say =E2=80=9Chuh you had a good year last year but the market was up, I h=
ave no idea if you=E2=80=99ll have a good year next year, I=E2=80=99m sure =
this stream of fees is worth something but it=E2=80=99s hard for me to know=
 how much=E2=80=9D and buy that stream of fees for a low price.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You, meanwhile, think that it=E2=80=99s worth a high p=
rice. For one thing, you have a lot of visibility into your deals and your =
pipeline and so you can underwrite your future performance better than an o=
utside investor can. For another thing, you have a lot of confidence in you=
rself, otherwise you wouldn=E2=80=99t be doing this.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">So the obvious move, for the managers of private equity firms, is=
 to sell off their management fees and keep their performance fees.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine various complicated financial-en=
gineering-y ways to do this (=E2=80=9Csecuritize the management fees=E2=80=
=9D or whatever), but in fact the simplest way to sell this stuff into a bi=
g liquid market is to do an initial public offering of=C2=A0<em>stock</em>,=
 that is,=C2=A0<em>ownership=C2=A0</em>of the entire private equity firm. S=
o if you manage private equity funds, you incorporate the management compan=
y that manages those funds, and then you sell shares in that company to the=
 public. And then the public owns (some share of) the entire income of that=
 management company, both the management fees (stable, sticky, valuable) an=
d the performance fees (variable, at-risk, discounted).=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Except that you continue to=C2=A0<em>run=C2=A0</em>the=
 firm. And you continue to set <em>employee=C2=A0compensation</em>. And so =
you can say to shareholders: =E2=80=9CYou know what, we=E2=80=99re going to=
 go public, but we=E2=80=99re going to keep paying ourselves all of the per=
formance fees, because we like those fees and you don=E2=80=99t, and you ca=
n have the management fees, because you like those fees more than we do.=E2=
=80=9D And that seems fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TPG Inc., a big=
 private equity firm,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/26356098.267642/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMjItMDEtMTIvYnV5b3V0LWZpcm0tdHBnLXNhaWQtdG8tcHJpY2UtaXBvLXdpdGhpbi1yY=
W5nZS1hdC0yOS01MC1hLXNoYXJlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRp=
dW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDExMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGF=
pZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc143467d" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">priced its i=
nitial public offering last night</a>, and it more or less did that? Here's=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26356098.267642/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNzU4MGQyNDQtY2ZiZC00NzI4LTk5YTktNDk5ODVl=
YjFmZGNk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB595599b9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Antoine Gara at the Fin=
ancial Times</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US buyout gro=
up TPG=E2=80=99s initial public offering on Thursday will establish a tecto=
nic change in the private equity industry, as a wave of firms list shares b=
y offering stockholders a smaller claim on their lucrative, but irregular, =
performance fees.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TPG is restructuring its =
finances as part of its IPO to offer shareholders just 20 per cent of its f=
uture performance-based profits, the firm said in its prospectus, down from=
 50 per cent had the change not been made.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Industry executives have dubbed TPG=E2=80=99s structure a =E2=80=9Cnext-gen=
eration=E2=80=9D private equity IPO =E2=80=94 one that gives public shareho=
lders less of a slice of performance fees, but more from steadier managemen=
t fees.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt is the new standard,=E2=
=80=9D said Saul Goodman, head of alternative asset management banking at E=
vercore. =E2=80=9CAlmost every banker in the space that=E2=80=99s advising =
private equity firms on IPOs currently is advising to not contribute a larg=
e percentage of performance fees into the public company.=E2=80=9D</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Analysts and investors are attracted to private equ=
ity=E2=80=99s management fee income because it is steady and easy to model,=
 according to bankers and private equity executives. Meanwhile, they discou=
nt performance-based profit because it can fluctuate with market conditions=
 and is harder to predict.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe pub=
lic values management fee earnings much more than the dealmakers inside fir=
ms, who are incentivised largely by carried interest,=E2=80=9D said Joseph =
Lombardo, head of the private equity general partnership advisory practice =
at investment bank Houlihan Lokey. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Publ=
icly traded firms have seen their valuations soar to 25 to 30 times their m=
anagement fee-based earnings, said insiders, but the groups still receive v=
aluations of just five to 10 times their investment profits.=C2=A0</p></blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The financial engineering required her=
e is pretty minimal, though TPG does a bit more than required. There=E2=80=
=99s an entity (=E2=80=9CRemainCo=E2=80=9D) that will be owned by TPG partn=
ers and will collect a slice of the performance fees that varies over time =
and from fund to fund, but you can ignore that;=C2=A0mostly the way the all=
ocation works is just that TPG has said, in a footnote to its financial sta=
tements, that it plans to pay most of the performance fees to employees. <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26356098.267642/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4ODA2NjEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTI=
yMDAwOTkzL2QxOTc3ODBkczFhLmh0bSNyb20xOTc3ODBfMTE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1=
e5e01a8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" t=
itle=3D"page 127" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">From the prospectus</a>:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Subject to certain exceptions, we expect Rema=
inCo to be entitled to between 10% and 15% of [performance fees], and to al=
locate generally between 65% and 70% indirectly to our partners and profess=
ionals through performance allocation vehicles and Promote Units, with the =
remaining 20% available for distribution to the TPG Operating Group Common =
Unit holders.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And because doin=
g this does not=C2=A0require that much in the way of legal structuring etc.=
, other already-public firms are doing it too; from Gara=E2=80=99s article:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Old-line listed private equity=
 firms are adjusting their economics to look more like newer entrants.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In February 2021, KKR revealed that it would ch=
ange the way it compensates employees, shifting from paying more than 40 pe=
r cent of overall management and performance-based fee earnings to insiders=
. Now, it pays up to 25 per cent of management fee-based earnings to employ=
ees, but up to 70 per cent of performance-fee-based earnings, a move that h=
as increased public shareholders=E2=80=99 claim on management fees and insi=
ders=E2=80=99 claim on performance profits.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Apollo said in November that it would cap pay for insiders at 25 per cent =
of management fee-based earnings, but raise payouts from performance fees f=
rom 50 per cent to as much as 70 per cent. Disclosures made by Blackstone i=
n the second quarter show it is making similar changes.</p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a pleasingly simple solution in a complex b=
usiness. =E2=80=9CWe are going to give shareholders the stuff they want and=
 keep the other stuff for ourselves.=E2=80=9D Why not?</p><table class=3D"l=
iveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=
=3D"center">
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"2">
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26356098.267642/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9zbGkuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9jbGljaz9zPTgyNTg4NSZsaT0yNjM1NjA5OCZtPTIxZ=
DZkZWE4MmQ2YjE2NjE1Y2Y0NDIzM2JlNjIwNTI1JnA9MjY2MjM3NDAmc3RwZT1kZWZhdWx0Jg/6=
